<ArticleLayout
  title="When a Family Member Faces Legal Jeopardy — A Guide for Advisors and Families"
  description="Navigating the intersection of criminal exposure, civil liability, and family wealth when a family member faces arrest, investigation, or prosecution."
  pillar="Crisis Navigation"
  pillarSlug="crisis-navigation"
>

  <p>
    The call arrives without warning. A family member has been arrested. A federal agent has appeared at a residence with a subpoena. A criminal defense attorney is requesting an emergency retainer. A domestic violence allegation has surfaced, and a protective order has been filed. However the notification arrives — and it will arrive, because criminal exposure is not a phenomenon confined to any socioeconomic stratum — the advisor who receives it confronts a crisis that sits at the intersection of criminal law, civil liability, family governance, wealth preservation, media risk, and human vulnerability. The response in the first seventy-two hours will shape outcomes that unfold over years. Sometimes permanently.
  </p>

  <p>
    Families of significant means face legal jeopardy with a distinct set of complications. The same wealth that provides access to exceptional legal talent also creates exposure that ordinary individuals never face. Asset forfeiture proceedings. Civil litigation that follows criminal allegations. Regulatory investigations that compound criminal risk. Media attention that transforms a private legal matter into a public spectacle. And the inescapable reality that prosecutors, plaintiffs' attorneys, and the court of public opinion all understand the family has resources worth pursuing. The advisor's role is not to practice law — that is the province of retained counsel. The role is to serve as the coordinating intelligence that ensures the family's response is integrated, disciplined, and aligned across every dimension of risk.
  </p>

  <p>
    The subject matter is uncomfortable. Every situation carries human suffering alongside legal complexity. The advisor's obligation to the family requires candor about realities that most people would prefer not to contemplate.
  </p>

  <h2>The First Seventy-Two Hours: Immediate Response Architecture</h2>

  <p>
    When a family member is arrested or becomes the subject of a criminal investigation, the first priority is securing competent criminal defense representation. This is not a task that can be delegated to the family's general counsel, their corporate litigation firm, or the attorney who drafted their estate plan. Criminal defense is a specialized practice, and the stakes of an inadequate defense — loss of liberty, felony conviction, sex offender registration, immigration consequences, professional license revocation — demand counsel who practices in the relevant jurisdiction, before the relevant court, with demonstrated experience in the specific category of charge.
  </p>

  <p>
    For UHNW families, the selection of criminal defense counsel involves considerations that extend beyond courtroom competence. The attorney must understand the collateral consequences that criminal proceedings create for wealthy defendants: the impact on trust structures, fiduciary appointments, business operations, regulatory relationships, and philanthropic commitments. They must be capable of coordinating with the family's existing legal team — estate counsel, tax advisors, corporate attorneys — without creating conflicts or inadvertently waiving privilege. And they must understand that for this category of client, a criminal charge is never an isolated legal event. It is a systemic shock that reverberates through every structure the family has built.
  </p>

  <h3>The Arrest Itself</h3>

  <p>
    If a family member has been arrested and is in custody, the immediate operational priorities are straightforward but critical. The individual should invoke their right to counsel and refrain from making any statements to law enforcement. This directive sounds elementary, but it is violated with remarkable frequency. Individuals who believe that their status, their articulateness, or the perceived triviality of the charge will allow them to talk their way out of custody are wrong. It will not. Statements made during custodial interrogation — even seemingly exculpatory statements — become evidence. The family member must be instructed, clearly and without equivocation, to remain silent until counsel is present.
  </p>

  <p>
    Bail or bond must be addressed promptly. For most misdemeanor charges, the family member may be released on their own recognizance or on a standard bond. For felony charges, particularly those involving violence, flight risk, or significant financial resources, bail hearings may be contested. Prosecutors in certain jurisdictions will argue that a wealthy defendant's resources constitute an enhanced flight risk, and the court may impose conditions — passport surrender, travel restrictions, GPS monitoring — that carry immediate practical implications. The advisor should ensure that defense counsel is prepared to address bail at the earliest opportunity and that the family understands the conditions of release before the individual returns home.
  </p>

  <h3>Parallel Civil Exposure</h3>

  <p>
    Criminal charges generate parallel civil liability. A DUI arrest that involves a collision will produce personal injury claims. Domestic violence allegations trigger protective orders and, in many cases, divorce proceedings. White-collar investigations create shareholder derivative actions, regulatory enforcement proceedings, and contractual disputes. Sexual misconduct allegations generate civil lawsuits that may be filed before, during, or after criminal proceedings. The advisor must recognize from the outset that the criminal case is only one front in what is typically a multi-front conflict, and that decisions made in the criminal context — plea negotiations, cooperation agreements, public statements — have consequences that cascade into every parallel proceeding.
  </p>

  <p>
    Defense counsel in the criminal matter must coordinate with the attorneys handling civil exposure, but coordination does not mean unification. The strategic interests in criminal defense and civil litigation are in tension. The Fifth Amendment privilege against self-incrimination, which protects a defendant in criminal proceedings, operates differently in civil litigation, where invoking the privilege may result in adverse inferences. The timing of civil discovery relative to criminal proceedings, the question of whether civil cases should be stayed pending criminal resolution, and the management of information flow between proceedings all require deliberate strategic choices that the family's legal team must address as an integrated unit.
  </p>

  <h2>Categories of Criminal Exposure and Their Particular Dynamics</h2>

  <h3>DUI/DWI and Vehicular Offenses</h3>

  <p>
    Driving under the influence remains the most common point of entry into the criminal justice system for individuals from affluent families. The charge may appear minor relative to other categories of criminal exposure, but advisors must resist the impulse to treat a DUI as a routine inconvenience. A first-offense DUI in most jurisdictions carries the possibility of jail time, license suspension, mandatory alcohol education, and significant fines. A DUI involving injury or death is a felony in virtually every jurisdiction, carrying potential prison sentences measured in years. Repeat offenses escalate penalties dramatically and, in many states, can be charged as felonies even absent injury.
  </p>

  <p>
    For UHNW families, the collateral consequences of a DUI extend far beyond the criminal penalties. Insurance implications across personal and business policies must be assessed. If the family member holds a professional license — in medicine, law, finance, or aviation — the licensing body will typically require disclosure and may initiate its own disciplinary proceedings. If the individual serves as a fiduciary — trustee, executor, corporate officer — the conviction may provide grounds for removal or disqualification. International travel may be affected, as several countries deny entry to individuals with DUI convictions. And if the arrest involved an accident, the civil exposure from personal injury claims can dwarf the criminal penalties by orders of magnitude.
  </p>

  <p>
    The advisor should also recognize that a DUI arrest is a signal of an <a href="/integrated-family-wellness/addiction-affluence-advisor-guide/">underlying substance use disorder</a>. The family's response to the legal crisis should address the legal dimension, certainly, but it should not ignore the behavioral health dimension. Defense counsel may pursue treatment-based dispositions — diversion programs, specialized DUI courts, probationary terms structured around monitored sobriety — and these alternatives are more credible and more effective when the defendant has already engaged meaningfully with treatment before the sentencing or disposition hearing.
  </p>

  <h3>Drug Charges</h3>

  <p>
    Drug charges present along a spectrum from simple possession of a controlled substance to trafficking and distribution. The distinction matters enormously. Simple possession charges, particularly for marijuana in jurisdictions where decriminalization or legalization has advanced, may be resolved with diversion programs, deferred adjudication, or minimal penalties. Possession of substances such as cocaine, heroin, methamphetamine, or illicit fentanyl carries more severe consequences and, in many jurisdictions, triggers mandatory minimum sentences if quantities exceed specified thresholds. Distribution or trafficking charges, even when the individual's actual conduct was more consistent with personal use and social sharing than commercial enterprise, can result in lengthy prison sentences and federal prosecution.
  </p>

  <p>
    Federal drug charges introduce a separate layer of complexity. The federal sentencing guidelines, while now advisory rather than mandatory following the Supreme Court's decision in United States v. Booker, still exert enormous influence on outcomes. Federal mandatory minimums for drug quantities can result in sentences of five, ten, or twenty years. Cooperation with the government — providing information about co-conspirators or assisting in ongoing investigations — is one of the very few mechanisms for obtaining a sentence below the mandatory minimum, and the decision whether to cooperate is among the most consequential choices the defendant and their counsel will face. It is also a decision that may have profound implications for the defendant's personal safety, family relationships, and business associations.
  </p>

  <p>
    The advisor must understand that drug charges in the UHNW context intersect with broader behavioral health concerns. An arrest for drug possession is the visible manifestation of a substance use disorder that the family may have been accommodating for years. The <a href="/crisis-navigation/behavioral-health-crisis-advisor-guide/">behavioral health crisis advisor guide</a> provides a framework for the clinical response that should accompany the legal strategy. The criminal case creates both risk and opportunity: risk, because a conviction carries severe consequences; opportunity, because the crisis may provide the impetus for treatment that the family's prior interventions failed to achieve. Defense counsel should explore diversion programs, drug court, and treatment-based alternatives to incarceration, but the family should understand that these alternatives demand genuine engagement with recovery, not performative compliance.
  </p>

  <h3>White-Collar Investigations and Financial Crimes</h3>

  <p>
    Federal and state investigations into financial crimes — fraud, tax evasion, money laundering, securities violations, embezzlement, Foreign Corrupt Practices Act violations — present a fundamentally different challenge than street-level criminal charges. White-collar investigations typically unfold over months or years before charges are filed. The family member may become aware of the investigation through a grand jury subpoena, a target letter from the U.S. Attorney's Office, a visit from federal agents, or notification from a business partner or co-defendant who has already been approached. The pre-indictment phase is the most consequential period in the entire proceeding, because decisions made during the investigation — whether to cooperate, how to respond to subpoenas, whether to assert privilege, how to preserve or produce documents — shape the government's case and the defendant's options. These early choices are extraordinarily difficult to reverse once charges are filed.
  </p>

  <p>
    For families with complex financial architectures, a white-collar investigation creates ripple effects that are both immediate and existential. Bank relationships may be terminated based on the investigation alone, before any charges are filed. Compliance departments at financial institutions operate under their own regulatory obligations and will file Suspicious Activity Reports, freeze accounts, and de-risk relationships with an efficiency that can leave the family financially dislocated within days. Business partners, co-investors, and counterparties may invoke morals clauses, key-person provisions, or default triggers in existing agreements. Philanthropic organizations may distance themselves from the family. The reputational damage from a white-collar investigation, unlike many other categories of criminal exposure, precedes and exceeds the legal consequences themselves.
  </p>

  <p>
    The advisor's role in a white-collar investigation is particularly complex because the investigation may encompass the very structures and transactions that the advisor manages. The family office's records, communications, and transaction history may be subject to subpoena. The advisor may be called as a witness. In extreme cases, the advisor's own conduct may come under scrutiny if the government believes that the family's professional advisors facilitated or failed to prevent the conduct under investigation. The advisor must engage independent legal counsel at the earliest indication of a white-collar investigation — not out of any presumption of personal liability, but as a matter of professional prudence and self-preservation.
  </p>

  <h3>Domestic Violence and Protective Orders</h3>

  <p>
    Domestic violence allegations present a distinctive constellation of challenges. The criminal charge itself — which may range from misdemeanor assault to felony aggravated domestic battery depending on the jurisdiction and the alleged conduct — is accompanied by a protective order that typically prohibits the accused from contacting the alleged victim, returning to the shared residence, and, in many cases, possessing firearms. For a family member whose primary residence is the family home, whose children reside with the alleged victim, and whose daily life is organized around the household from which they are now excluded, the protective order creates an immediate and disorienting disruption.
  </p>

  <p>
    The advisor must navigate these situations with particular care. Domestic violence is a genuine and serious public health concern, and the advisor's role is not to assume either the guilt or innocence of the accused family member. The role is to ensure that the family member has competent criminal defense counsel, that the terms of the protective order are understood and scrupulously followed, that the family's financial obligations — mortgage payments, household expenses, children's needs — continue to be met despite the disruption, and that the family's legal team is coordinating across the criminal, family law, and asset protection dimensions of the matter. Violations of protective orders, even technical violations such as sending a text message to the protected party or returning to the residence to retrieve personal items, are independently criminal and will devastate the defendant's credibility and legal position.
  </p>

  <p>
    Domestic violence cases in UHNW families are further complicated by the intersection with matrimonial law. The criminal case may trigger divorce proceedings, and the divorce will introduce its own discovery process, financial disclosure requirements, and custody determinations. The family's financial architecture — trusts, prenuptial agreements, business interests, real property holdings — becomes relevant in both proceedings. Information disclosed in the criminal case may be used in the divorce, and vice versa. The advisor must ensure that the family's legal team recognizes and manages these interdependencies, because a misstep in one proceeding can have devastating consequences in the other.
  </p>

  <h3>Sexual Misconduct Allegations</h3>

  <p>
    Allegations of sexual misconduct — whether charged as sexual assault, rape, statutory offenses, indecent exposure, solicitation, or offenses involving minors — represent the highest-stakes category of criminal exposure. The potential penalties, including lengthy prison sentences and mandatory sex offender registration that persists for decades or for life, are severe. The reputational consequences are catastrophic and permanent, regardless of the case's ultimate disposition. The emotional toll on the accused, the accuser, and the broader family is profound and enduring.
  </p>

  <p>
    Sexual misconduct cases require defense counsel with highly specific expertise. The forensic evidence considerations, the dynamics of delayed disclosure, the applicable statutes of limitations, the evidentiary rules governing prior acts and character evidence, and the particular intensity of prosecutorial and public attention that these cases attract all demand specialized knowledge. The advisor should ensure that counsel has a demonstrated record in this specific area and that the defense team includes investigators, forensic experts, and — where appropriate — expert witnesses who can address the clinical and scientific dimensions of the case. The advisor must also be prepared for the reality that sexual misconduct allegations will test the family's cohesion, the advisor's own equanimity, and the capacity of every professional involved to maintain objectivity under conditions of extreme emotional pressure.
  </p>

  <h2>Wealth-Specific Complications in Criminal Proceedings</h2>

  <h3>Asset Preservation and Forfeiture Risk</h3>

  <p>
    Federal and state forfeiture statutes allow the government to seize assets that are alleged to be the proceeds of criminal activity or that were used to facilitate criminal conduct. In white-collar cases, forfeiture can extend to bank accounts, real estate, vehicles, investment portfolios, and business interests. The government may seek pre-trial restraining orders that freeze assets before any conviction, effectively depriving the defendant of the resources needed to fund their defense. This is not an abstract risk — it is a routine feature of federal financial crime prosecutions, and the Supreme Court's recognition of a defendant's Sixth Amendment right to counsel of choice has not eliminated the government's ability to restrain assets it can trace to alleged criminal activity.
  </p>

  <p>
    The family's estate and asset protection counsel must be engaged immediately to assess forfeiture exposure, identify assets that may be traceable to alleged criminal conduct, and develop strategies for preserving assets that are legitimately beyond the reach of forfeiture. Trust structures, family limited partnerships, and corporate entities may provide some insulation, but these structures will be scrutinized aggressively, and any transfers made after the investigation begins will be challenged as fraudulent conveyances. The time to build asset protection architecture is before a crisis materializes — but when the crisis has already arrived, a candid assessment of exposure is the necessary starting point.
  </p>

  <h3>Media Risk and Reputational Management</h3>

  <p>
    Criminal charges against a member of a prominent family will attract media attention. The <a href="/crisis-navigation/reputational-crisis-management-private-families/">reputational crisis management framework</a> addresses this dimension in depth. The degree of attention varies with the nature of the charge, the family's public profile, and the appetite of the local and national press, but the advisor should assume that any arrest, indictment, or significant court proceeding will become a matter of public record and public discussion. Mugshots, booking records, court filings, and — in some jurisdictions — body camera footage may become publicly available through records requests or court proceedings.
  </p>

  <p>
    The family's communications strategy must be developed in close coordination with defense counsel, because public statements by or on behalf of the defendant can become evidence. The instinct to issue a forceful public denial, to litigate the case in the media, or to attack the credibility of the accuser is almost always counterproductive and harmful to the legal defense. Defense counsel should be the sole arbiter of what is said publicly about the case. The family's communications advisors can manage the broader narrative — supporting the family's institutional reputation, managing social media exposure, and preparing for press inquiries — but any statement that touches on the facts of the case must be vetted by defense counsel before it is released.
  </p>

  <h3>Impact on Fiduciary Roles and Institutional Relationships</h3>

  <p>
    A criminal charge — and, in many cases, a mere investigation — can disqualify an individual from fiduciary roles. Trust instruments include provisions that remove a trustee upon felony conviction or indictment. Corporate bylaws may require the resignation of officers or directors who face criminal charges. Professional licensing boards in medicine, law, accounting, and financial services impose their own standards, which may be triggered by arrest, charge, or conviction depending on the jurisdiction and the profession. The advisor must conduct an immediate inventory of every fiduciary, corporate, and professional role held by the accused family member and assess the applicable standards and triggers for each.
  </p>

  <p>
    Succession planning for these roles must begin immediately, drawing on the principles of <a href="/family-governance/governance-for-complex-families/">governance for complex families</a>, even if the family hopes or expects that the charges will be resolved favorably. The period between arrest and resolution — which may span months or years — creates a governance vacuum that the family cannot afford to leave unaddressed. Temporary appointments, powers of attorney, delegation authorities, and board resolutions should be prepared and, where appropriate, executed promptly to ensure continuity of management and compliance with institutional obligations.
  </p>

  <h2>The Advisor's Role: Coordination, Not Counsel</h2>

  <p>
    The advisor — whether a wealth manager, family office director, trust officer, or fiduciary counsel — is not the criminal defense attorney and must not attempt to function in that capacity. The advisor's value lies in seeing the full architecture of the family's interests and ensuring every professional engaged in the crisis works within a coherent strategic framework. This coordination function is indispensable. Criminal defense counsel, civil litigation attorneys, family law counsel, tax advisors, communications consultants, security professionals — each operates within their own domain. They do not see the interdependencies between their respective engagements. They do not prioritize them. The advisor must.
  </p>

  <p>
    The advisor must also serve as a stabilizing presence for the family. Criminal charges against a family member produce fear, shame, anger, grief, and — not infrequently — division within the family about how to respond. Some family members will want to provide unconditional support. Others will want to distance themselves. Financial questions will surface immediately: Who is paying for the defense? From which accounts? Under what authority? Does the family's governance structure contemplate this contingency? These questions must be addressed with clarity and transparency, because unresolved financial tensions will compound the crisis and undermine the family's ability to respond effectively.
  </p>

  <p>
    The advisor should also be the person who ensures that the family addresses the human dimension of the crisis — not only the legal and financial dimensions. A family member facing criminal charges is under extraordinary stress, and the risk of behavioral health deterioration, including substance relapse, depression, anxiety, and suicidal ideation, is elevated. The <a href="https://www.nami.org/About-Mental-Illness/Common-with-Mental-Illness/Risk-of-Suicide" target="_blank" rel="noopener">National Alliance on Mental Illness</a> offers resources on recognizing warning signs. The advisor should ensure that the family member has access to appropriate <a href="/integrated-family-wellness/mental-health-uhnw-families/">mental health support</a> and that the defense team is aware of any behavioral health concerns that may affect the legal strategy or the individual's capacity to participate in their own defense.
  </p>

  <h2>After Resolution: Expungement, Restoration, and Lessons Learned</h2>

  <p>
    If the criminal matter is resolved favorably — through dismissal, acquittal, or a disposition that avoids conviction — the advisor should immediately pursue every available mechanism for clearing the record. Expungement, sealing, or setting aside of charges varies dramatically by jurisdiction, but the failure to pursue these remedies leaves the family member permanently vulnerable to background checks, media references, and the downstream consequences of an arrest record that need not persist. Defense counsel should advise on the applicable procedures and timelines, and the advisor should ensure that the process is completed, not merely initiated.
  </p>

  <p>
    If the matter results in a conviction, the advisor's role shifts to managing the consequences: compliance with sentencing terms, restoration of civil rights upon completion of sentence, management of collateral consequences across professional and fiduciary roles, and — where appropriate — support for the family member's reintegration into the family's governance and institutional structures. A conviction is not the end of the story. Families that treat it as such abandon a family member at their most vulnerable and forgo the opportunity to rebuild structures that are stronger for having been tested.
  </p>

  <p>
    The advisor should facilitate an honest post-crisis review using the following framework:
  </p>

  <h3>Post-Crisis Review Checklist</h3>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Professional readiness:</strong> Were qualified criminal defense, civil litigation, and crisis communications professionals identified and accessible when the crisis struck — or did the family scramble to find them under pressure?</li>
    <li><strong>Governance authority:</strong> Did the family's governance structure provide clear authority for decision-making during the emergency, or did ambiguity create delay and conflict?</li>
    <li><strong>Trust and corporate instruments:</strong> Were trust instruments, operating agreements, and corporate documents adequate to address the contingency — including provisions for suspension, removal, or succession?</li>
    <li><strong>Information protocols:</strong> Did communication protocols prevent inadvertent privilege waivers and discovery exposure, or did informal channels create vulnerability?</li>
    <li><strong>Financial response:</strong> Was there clarity about who authorized defense expenditures, from which accounts, and under what governance authority?</li>
    <li><strong>Behavioral health monitoring:</strong> Was the family member's mental health adequately supported throughout the legal process, including screening for substance relapse, depression, and suicidal ideation?</li>
    <li><strong>Family cohesion:</strong> Did the crisis reveal unresolved tensions within the family, and have those been addressed through governance reform or facilitated dialogue?</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The answers should inform structural improvements that reduce the impact of future incidents, ideally integrated into the family's <a href="/crisis-navigation/fiduciary-crisis-preparedness-framework/">crisis preparedness framework</a>. The lesson of every legal crisis is that preparedness is not pessimism. It is the foundation of responsible stewardship.
  </p>

  <h2>Crisis Resources</h2>

  <p>
    Legal crises frequently co-occur with behavioral health emergencies, including substance use disorders, suicidal ideation, and acute psychological distress. The following resources are available twenty-four hours a day, seven days a week:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>988 Suicide &amp; Crisis Lifeline:</strong> Call or text <strong>988</strong> for immediate support during a mental health crisis, suicidal thoughts, or emotional distress. Available 24/7 with trained counselors.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>SAMHSA National Helpline:</strong> Call <strong>1-800-662-4357</strong> (1-800-662-HELP) for free, confidential, 24/7 referrals to treatment facilities, support groups, and community-based organizations for substance use disorders and mental health conditions. Visit <a href="https://www.samhsa.gov/find-help/national-helpline" target="_blank" rel="noopener">samhsa.gov</a> for additional resources.
  </p>

